SIMPLE: risible
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Risible
<hw>Ris"i*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L.
<ets>risibilis</ets>, fr. <ets>ridere</ets>, <ets>risum</ets>, to laugh.
Cf. <er>Ridiculous</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having the faculty or
power of laughing; disposed to laugh.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Laughing is our busines, . . . it has been made the definition of
man that he is <qex>risible</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Dr. H.
More.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Exciting laughter; worthy to be laughed at;
amusing.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Risible</xex> absurdities.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I hope you find nothing <qex>risible</qex> in my complaisance.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Used in, or expressing, laughter; <as>as,
<ex>risible</ex> muscles</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Risible</xex> is sometimes used as a noun, in the
plural, for the feeling of amusement and for the muscles and other
organs used in laughing, collectively; as, unable to control one's
<xex>risibles</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Ludicrous; laughable; amusing; ridiculous --
<er>Risible</er>, <er>Ludicrous</er>, <er>Ridiculous</er>.</syn> <usage>
<xex>Risible</xex> differs from <xex>ludicrous</xex> as species from
genus; <xex>ludicrous</xex> expressing that which is playful and
sportive; <xex>risible</xex>, that which may excite laughter.
<xex>Risible</xex> differs from <xex>ridiculous</xex>, as the latter
implies something contemptuous, and <xex>risible</xex> does
not.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1245 --></p>

<p>--<wordforms><wf>Ris"i*ble*ness</wf><pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> --
<wf>Ris"i*bly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rising</ent>⟦br⟧
